We almost saw 2.4M yesterday, but not quite. 2 more likely days remaining in the forecast period: this coming Friday and Sunday. We can't compare with 2019 for those days because the days shown in the table correspond to Memorial Day weekend in 2019. So at this point, it all depends on how likely one thinks it is that travel numbers will go up enough. I don't think travel supply is yet saturated, and it would just take a slight bump up compared to yesterday to reach 2.4M. And I expect travel demand to generally increase through the rest of the month. If it increases even slightly, 2.4M will be reached this coming weekend. Also, on the theory that what goes up must come down, if we saw nearly 2.4M yesterday, I think we can expect to see some similarly high numbers this weekend. So, I'm raising my forecast.

It’s been a really interesting debate trying to figure out how to assess the odds correctly on this one. On the one hand we have a clear set of the likeliest days based on 2019 data, but then we also have macro factors like the economy, rising interest rates (and covid cases), along with plane loading data and an expected trend of increasing travel through May. And the irony that while the most likely dates are towards the end of the forecast period, Memorial Day does not even fall within the timeframe this year.

I live in Alaska. Most people fly in/out of the state for vacations and business, especially now that the cruise industry is still struggling with COVID issues . Alaska Airlines is our one major air carrier, so when Alaska Airlines has problems, everyone here notices. This story has become nearly daily headline news here. I've read that other airlines are having the same issues, but because most markets have more than one carrier and people can always drive to/from places in the lower 48, the problems have not impacted people as severely as they have here.
EDIT:

2,327,671 on Thursday, 5/12, 87.5% of the corresponding 2019 value. This is the highest Thursday number we have seen in the forecast period, excluding Easter weekend. This is the lowest Thursday percentage to date; the previous range was 88.4% to 99.1%, excluding Easter weekend. Except around Easter, Fridays have averaged 2.5% greater than the day before, range 0.6%-4.6%. The most recent Friday was 2.0% higher than the day before. So I'll expect Friday's number to be between 2.342M and 2.435, probably closer to the expected average 2.5% higher number, 2.386M or just below. So I give Friday a ~48% chance of exceeding 2.4M, if we say that this week's numbers are likely to end up averaging ~89.5% of 2019 numbers, or a ~36% chance based on the typical pattern of Fridays vs. Thursdays. I give Sunday a ~50% chance of exceeding 2.4M, if we say that this week's numbers are likely to end up averaging ~89.5% of 2019 numbers, or looking at the ratios of Sundays to the Thursdays before, I get a ~40% chance that this coming Sunday will see 2.4M or more. If we average it all out to ~40% chance that today or Sunday will individually see 2.4M or more, and project the same odds for next weekend, this would give an 88% chance of seeing 2.4M either this weekend or next weekend. So I'll lower my forecast slightly to 85%. It's possible that next weekend will see more traffic than this one, too.

Mean of 2022 levels vs. 2019 has been 89% with a sd of 3.5%. Dip size is pretty normally distributed, so you can calculate a z-score for the necessary dip size to be above 2.4M using that mean and sd, and get probability from there. I.e. the 2019 value for 5/21 is 2.79M, 2.4M would mean 2022 would need to be 86% of 2019, or z-score of -0.87. The chance of 2.4M or above in that framework is 81%.

Following belikewater. Thanks for doing the math!

If you plot out the numbers for each date for March 16 through May 25 for each year, here's what they look like: * First, note that the source data table gives "TSA checkpoint travel numbers (current year versus prior year(s)/same weekday)"; in other words, the number for a date in one year is compared against the number for the same date in another year, shifted by 1 or more days so that it's on the same weekday. * A somewhat noisy weekly pattern is clear: ** The lowest numbers are usually on Saturdays (with occasional exceptions) and mid-week, usually Tuesdays and Wednesdays. ** The highest numbers are usually on Fridays and Sundays, with occasional exceptions. ** Generally, Mondays are almost as high as Sundays, and Thursdays are almost as high as Fridays. * In 2019, from Easter weekend onward in the forecast period, the lowest numbers were on Saturdays; Tuesdays weren't quite as low. In 2021, throughout the entire forecast period, the pattern was reversed: the lowest numbers were mid-week, and Saturdays weren't quite as low. (Does this mean more travel was more business travel in 2021 than in 2019? I'm not sure what to make of this switch.) So far, 2022 has followed the same pattern as 2021. * The numbers were really low in 2020. * The numbers in 2021 were a bit more than half of those in 2019. The numbers on each day in this period in 2021 were an average of 61% of those in 2019. The numbers in 2021 also started to climb closer to the 2019 numbers throughout the forecast period (and beyond). * The numbers in 2022 in the forecast period so far are slightly beneath those in 2019 and track the shape of the 2019 curve very well. * 2-5 days each week in the forecast period in 2019 saw numbers above 2.4M.

Out of the 79 days between 08MAR and 25MAY, in 2019 16 of those days had over 2.4 million persons screened (https://www.tsa.gov/coronavirus/passenger-throughput). The year 2022 is approaching 2019 travel numbers.

The outside view is the frequency before COVID, which is nearly 100%. Another problem could be rising flight prices due to recent uncertainties, but I think that its effects would be minor.

I added in the latest week of data and the cumulative probability I get is now 54%. That it shifted from 16 to 54% with one week of new data means the basic premise that the mean is stationary is probably wrong. So I have added a large margin to assume further shifts in the same direction will happen.

Given the number of days remaining and the likelihood of increasing travel over the short term I think this is very likely. We've been close twice in the last week at just under 2.3M, with Easter holidays approaching. Already over 2.2m around Spring Break. So long as Covid keeps receding, the numbers should gradually increase, and perhaps cross 2.4 million by Easter.

Going by the limited TSA data available it looks like mid-March is a local seasonal peak, with the next peaks being around Easter and Memorial day. 2019 saw a spike on 5/24, which was the Friday before Memorial day. However, that day would be 5/27 this year, two days after the question closes. There's also a brief bump around Easter during the trough that the rest of April is. So the way I see it, there's a chance we hit it this Friday during a seasonal high, a chance around Easter, and a chance before Memorial day. Otherwise, normal Friday/weekend levels appear to peak right below it around 2.2M or 2.3M.

This has happened 40(?) times in the past three years. April is a historically popular month for travel. Though travel numbers are beginning to return to pre-pandemic levels, they're still lagging. I would place my prediction closer to 50%, but I think the recent BA.2 will dampen travel.

Using year-to-date (YTD) average and standard deviations for each day of the week the highest probably of being hit was a Friday where the target is 2.16 standard deviations from the average.
